    <body>
      <head>Elfriede (Therese Anna Elisabeth) Oppel (<hi rend="italic">née</hi> Dey)</head>
      <div>

        <p>The fourth wife of <ref cRef="entity-000643">Reinhard Oppel</ref>.</p>

        <p><ref cRef="entity-000643">Reinhard Oppel</ref> and Elfriede Dey married on May 30, 1930
          in <ref cRef="entity-002479">Leipzig</ref>. When they met in 1929 Elfriede was a piano
          student at the <ref cRef="entity-002872">Leipzig Conservatory</ref>, where <ref
            cRef="entity-000643">Reinhard</ref> taught. The couple had two children: <ref
            cRef="entity-008523">Kurt (“Bepo”)</ref>, born 1930 and <ref cRef="entity-008524"
            >Brigitte</ref>, born 1932; Elfriede also looked after <ref cRef="entity-000643"
            >Reinhard</ref>’s three sons from his second marriage: <ref cRef="entity-000644"
            >Ulrich</ref>, <ref cRef="entity-003957">Walter</ref>, and <ref cRef="entity-008510"
            >Hans Reinhard</ref>. Of having remarried, <ref cRef="entity-000643">Reinhard</ref>
          remarked that he did so: “more in the interest of the boys than for my own sake” (<ref
            type="correspondence" cRef="OJ-13-10_104">OJ 13/10, [104]</ref>, June 17, 1930).</p>

        <p>Elfriede outlived <ref cRef="entity-000643">Reinhard</ref> at his death in 1941, and
          helped conceal his music during World War II, when the Oppel family fled to west Germany.
          After the war she sought to advocate for <ref cRef="entity-000643">Reinhard</ref>’s
          work.</p>

      </div>
